Question 2

library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)

data_2002 <- data_2002 %>%
  rename(
    date = 'Date',
    pm = 'Daily Mean PM2.5 Concentration',
    site = 'Site ID',
    county = 'County',
    site_name = 'Local Site Name',
    lat = 'Site Latitude',
    lon = 'Site Longitude'
  ) %>%
  mutate(year = year(mdy(date))) %>%
  select(-date) 
data_2022 <- data_2022 %>%
  rename(
    date = 'Date',
    pm = 'Daily Mean PM2.5 Concentration',
    site = 'Site ID',
    county = 'County',
    site_name = 'Local Site Name',
    lat = 'Site Latitude',
    lon = 'Site Longitude'
  ) %>%
  mutate(year = year(mdy(date))) %>%
  select(-date) 

data_all <- bind_rows(data_2002, data_2022)

Question 3

library(leaflet)
library(leafsync)

sites <- data_all %>%
  distinct(year, site, lat, lon, county) %>%
  filter(!is.na(lat), !is.na(lon))

s2002 <- filter(sites, year == 2002)
s2022 <- filter(sites, year == 2022)

map2002 <- leaflet(s2002) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    ~lon, ~lat,
    color= "blue", radius= 4,
    stroke= FALSE, fillOpacity= 0.8,
    popup= ~paste("Site:", site, "<br>County:", county)
  ) %>%
  addLegend("bottomright", colors= "blue", labels = "2002", title = "Monitoring Sites")

map2022 <- leaflet(s2022) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    ~lon, ~lat,
    color= "red", radius= 4,
    stroke= FALSE, fillOpacity= 0.8,
    popup= ~paste("Site:", site, "<br>County:", county)
  ) %>%
  addLegend("bottomright", colors= "red", labels = "2022", title = "Monitoring Sites")

leafsync::sync(map2002, map2022)

From the comparison of these two maps, the distribution of monitoring sites in California is broadly the same between 2002 and 2022, 2022 has a substantial increase in the overall number of sites but following the same broad distribution. 2002 has noticeable gaps in rural area whereas in 2022 the coverage in rural and inland area increased.

Question 4

max_pm <- 200 #googled an arbitrary range
min_pm <- 0

pm_issue <- data_all %>%
  mutate(
    missing = is.na(pm),
    implausible = pm < min_pm | pm > max_pm
  ) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    n_total= n(),
    n_missing= sum(missing),
    n_implausible= sum(implausible, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

print(pm_issue)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 4
   year n_total n_missing n_implausible
  <dbl>   <int>     <int>         <int>
1  2002   15976         0             0
2  2022   59918         0           222

Both years have no missing values, but in 2022 there are 222 observations that exceeded the max range compared to 0 in 2002, suggesting that the range of pm in 2022 got larger and there are more extremely high PM days in 2022 (like 2022 has worse PM / air quality).

Question 5

library(ggplot2)
state_summary <- data_all %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_pm = mean(pm, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_pm = median(pm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_pm = sd(pm, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n()
  )
print(state_summary)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 5
   year mean_pm median_pm sd_pm     n
  <dbl>   <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl> <int>
1  2002   16.1       12   13.9  15976
2  2022    8.41       6.8  7.64 59918
ggplot(data_all, aes(x = factor(year), y= pm, fill= factor(year))) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.alpha = 0.2) +
  labs(title = "PM2.5 in California (2002 vs 2022)", x= "year", y = "PM2.5")

On a state level, the result shows a clear reduction in PM2.5 between 2002 and 2022. The median PM decreased from 16.1 to 8.4, same goes for the decrease in range observed in the boxplot.

However, the boxplot also reveal that the outliers in 2022 shows more extreme outlier days, suggesting that while the overall conditions got cleaner, there are still occasional more severe pollution events.

county_summary <- data_all %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_2002= mean(pm[year==2002], na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_2022= mean(pm[year==2022], na.rm = TRUE),
    diff_pm= mean(pm[year == 2022], na.rm = TRUE)- mean(pm[year == 2002], na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  arrange(county)

At a county level, the dumbbell chart shows that all except Del Norte recorded a decrease in PM level from 2002 to 2022. Even for Del Norte, the change is ~1.15, relatively small compared to other changes. Meanwhile, Kern, Kings, Mendocino, and Riverside all have over -10 decrease in PM2.5 between 2002 and 2022. Overall, both the chart and the table shows that all but one county experienced decrease in their PM2.5 level between 2002 and 2022.
